      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Glucose exists in two forms having a 36:64 ratio at equilibrium. Draw a skeletal structure of each, describe the difference between them, and tell which of the two you think is more stable (red = O).</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBa3NSIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--86c54380ce0e9202712b137ddc43ea630ba7f3b2/OChem_04_EC_005.jpg\" alt=\"The ball and stick models of alpha-glucose and beta-glucose. In alpha-glucose, C1 is bonded to an axial hydroxyl group (below the ring). In beta-glucose, C1 is bonded to an equatorial hydroxyl group (above the ring).\">",
